Assignment #1 - Linear Regression¶

Introduction¶

Aim: This assignment work aims to how Linear regression works on data and how predictions can be made effieciently using Least square and Least Mean square method.

Implementation of two methods is done in this assignment 1. Least squares method 2. Least mean squares method.

We will train our model using these two methods and then see how those models works while doing prediction.

Also in order to get stable data we will see how preprocessing and cleaning of data is done.

Data¶

This dataset includes a hourly/daily summary for Szeged, Hungary area, between 2006 and 2016.

Data available in the hourly response:

.Formatted Date
.summary
.precipType
.temperature
.apparent Temperature
.humidity
.windSpeed
.windBearing
.visibility
.loudCover
.pressure

Description¶

Apparent Temperature is the temperature equivalent perceived by humans, casued by the combined effects of air temperature, humdity, wind speed and windbearing. Relationship between different variables with apparent temperature using regression model. Also we can see some features are least significant and some are more significant.

Source : https://www.kaggle.com/budincsevity/szeged-weather

Method¶

Summarize the linear models (least-squares and LMS) and explain your implementation of class LinearModel. The explanation of your codes should not be the comments in a code cell. This section should include

Review of the linear models¶

Least Squares¶

The parameter that gives best fit will be

$$ w^* = \arg\min_wv \sum_{i=1}{N} \Big( f(xv_i; wv) - t_i \Big)^2 $$

We use Least Squares method because we are looking for a probabilistic model that fits the observed data best and can be used for future prediction. The least squares model does much better in fitting a curve than many methods such as plotting the average slope of all the slopes between the pait of points ( x E X , t E T )

We can solve this by, setting derivative with respect to w to zero. After solving this we will get the normal function

$$ \begin{align} w &= \big(X^\top X\big)^{-1} X^\top t \end{align} $$

Where X is our independent variables data and T is target variable.

Implementation:

A LinearRegress class is defined with initialization of base class as LinearModel where weight 'w' is initizlized as None. Class LinearModel has two function which we will use later in the code.

1.check_matrix : This function check the dimension of the matrix. If dimensions are not equal to 2 it throws exception.
2.add_ones : This function is used to create column in X input by adding 1, so that matrix operations can be performed correctly.

LinearRegress class has 2 important functions:

1.train() : This function accepts 2 arguments , first is X, input array (independent variable data) and second is T (target label) data. We have implemented equation of the normal function in train function which calculates the value of w.
2.use() : This function is used to prdict the new values using w calculated in train function using testing data's features.

Least Mean squares¶

In Least Squares, we are using the whole dataset to calculate the value of w, this can be very costly if the dataset is large. When data is sufficiently large, we can consider sequential or online learning using Least Mean Squares method. During the online learning process, we introduce a data point one by one, and update the parameters. Using the updated parameters, it makes a new estimation and repeat these steps.

For this, we start with an initial guess $w$ and changes it as it reads more data until it converges. When $k$ represents the steps for the repetition,

$$ w^{(k+1)} = w^{(k)} - \alpha \nabla E_k $$

where $E_k$ is the error for the $k$'th sample and $\alpha$ is a learning rate. This is called stochastic gradient descent or sequential gradient descent.

For the $k$'th sample $x_k$, the gradient for the sum-of-squares error is

Solving this gives us:

$$ w^{(k+1)} = w^{(k)} - \alpha \Big( {w^{(k)}}^\top x_k - t_k \Big) x_k. $$

Implementation

In LMS also same super and base class are used as in LS. One additional class as LMS is created which has following functions:

1.train(): train function calls train_step function for each sample.
2.train_step(): train_step function adds ones to x and then initializes w(once) and start calculating value of w till it converges.
3.use(): use function will give the dot product of X and w which is nothing but the predicted value.

Also in LMS class, when we are creating a model, we need to pass the alpha value, i.e the learning rate.

Super Classs Definition¶

In [513]:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

# Super class for machine learning models 

class BaseModel(ABC):
    """ Super class for ITCS Machine Learning Class"""
    
    @abstractmethod
    def train(self, X, T):
        pass

    @abstractmethod
    def use(self, X):
        pass

    
class LinearModel(BaseModel):
   
    """
        Abstract class for a linear model 
        
        Attributes
        ==========
        w       ndarray
                weight vector/matrix
    """

    def __init__(self):
        """
            weight vector w is initialized as None
        """
        self.w = None

    def _check_matrix(self, mat, name):
        if len(mat.shape) != 2:
            raise ValueError(''.join(["Wrong matrix ", name]))
        
    # add a basis
    def add_ones(self, X):
        """
            add a column basis to X input matrix
        """
        self._check_matrix(X, 'X')
        return np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0], 1)), X))

    ####################################################
    #### abstract funcitons ############################
    @abstractmethod
    def train(self, X, T):
        """
            train linear model
            
            parameters
            -----------
            X     2d array
                  input data
            T     2d array
                  target labels
        """        
        pass
    
    @abstractmethod
    def use(self, X):
        """
            apply the learned model to input X
            
            parameters
            ----------
            X     2d array
                  input data
            
        """        
        pass

Least Squares¶

In [514]:
# Linear Regression Class for least squares
class LinearRegress(LinearModel): 
    
    """ 
        LinearRegress class 
        
        attributes
        ===========
        w    nd.array
             weights
    """
    def __init__(self):
        LinearModel.__init__(self)
                
    # train lease-squares model
    def train(self, X, T):
        X = self.add_ones(X)
        self.w = np.linalg.lstsq(X.T @ X, X.T @ T)[0]
        return self.w
    
    # apply the learned model to data X
    def use(self, X):
        X = self.add_ones(X)
        return X @ self.w

Least Mean Squares¶

In [515]:
import collections # for checking iterable instance

# LMS class 
class LMS(LinearModel):
    """
        Lease Mean Squares. online learning algorithm
    
        attributes
        ==========
        w        nd.array
                 weight matrix
        alpha    float
                 learning rate
    """
    def __init__(self, alpha):
        LinearModel.__init__(self)
        self.alpha = alpha
    
    # batch training by using train_step function
    def train(self, X, T):
        # Iterate over all values of X and T
        for x, t in zip(X, T):
            # Call to train_Step function
            self.train_step(x, t)
        return self.w
            
    # train LMS model one step 
    # here the x is 1d vector
    def train_step(self, x, t):
        x = np.insert(x, 0, 1).reshape(-1, 1)
        # Initialize weight w in first run
        if self.w is None:
            self.w = np.zeros((x.shape[0], 1))
        # Calculate weight w
        self.w = np.subtract(self.w, (self.alpha * (self.w.T @ x - t) * x))
        
    # apply the current model to data X
    def use(self, X):
        X = self.add_ones(X)
        t = self.w.T @ X.T
        return t.T

In [521]:
def plot_ls(ytest,T):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.plot(ytest.values[0::10], label='Target Values', color='red')
    plt.plot(T[0::10], label='Predicted Values', color = 'blue')
    plt.xlabel('Data with 10 intervals', fontsize=14)
    plt.ylabel('Apparent Temperature', fontsize=14)
    plt.title('1. Least Square Model: RMSE value: '+ str(rmse(ytest.values,T)), fontsize=14)
    plt.legend()
    print()

def split_dataframe(df):
    Xtrain = df[['Humidity','Wind Speed (km/h)','Wind Bearing (degrees)','Visibility (km)']].head(8000)
    Xtest = df[['Humidity','Wind Speed (km/h)','Wind Bearing (degrees)','Visibility (km)']].tail(2000)
    ytrain = df['Apparent Temperature (C)'].head(8000)
    ytest = df['Apparent Temperature (C)'].tail(2000)
    return Xtrain,ytrain,Xtest,ytest
